                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.52/112a.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Consul <persName type="to">Hamm</persName>.</hi>
                    <note n="110" xml:id="d1341fn110">Same telegram to Vice Consul Simpich at
                        Nogales.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-01-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 7, 1914</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Spanish Embassy states it is in receipt of telegram from Spanish Minister, Mexico
                    City, saying that Arredondo, Municipal Chief of Guanacevi, Durango, under orders
                    from Villa is about to confiscate the mine El Desengaño, alleging owners were
                    taking part in Mexican politics. Mine said to be owned by Spanish subjects, two
                    Mexicans and an American citizen.</p>
                <p>Use your good offices with revolutionary leaders to see that this property
                    receives protection.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
